docs.lead_paragraph: A 106-degree fever with teeth-clenching chills would frighten anyone, and when the cause cannot be identified quickly, such symptoms are even more alarming. For nearly two weeks beginning in late October, Sean Cavanaugh, a 30-year-old artist in Manhattan, had fevers that spiked to 104 and 106 degrees. Last week, his doctors diagnosed malaria.

headline.main: Diagnosis Was Malaria, but Experts Disagreed on the Source

docs.abstract: Fever that has laid low Sean Cavanaugh, a New York artist, for two weeks is diagnosed as malaria, and he is beginning to respond to anti-malarial therapy; two experts at Centers for Disease Control believe he contracted disease during visit to Honduras in the spring; others suspect a mosquito on Long Island, where Cavanagh was this September and where two Boy Scouts came down with malaria in August; photo (M)
